Sixty percent of Canadians would like to see an  increase in trade with Japan, but a majority also feels Japan should do more  to protect the environment and contribute more to international peacekeeping,  a new poll reveals.
The Angus Reid poll, conducted for the Japanese Government, found that,  while 60 percent of Canadians favored increased trade with Japan, only 25  percent believed increased bilateral trade would help the Canadian economy.
The overall Canadian view of Japanese people is positive with 86 percent  of poll respondents describing the Japanese as hardworking and 65 percent  describing the Japanese as energetic.
Just 12 percent said they believed the Japanese to be unsociable.
A majority -- 62 percent -- said they believed Japan should play a more  active role in peacekeeping and 56 percent said Japan should contribute more  to protecting the Earth's environment.
